Threat Report

 

Threat Actor Update: Lazarus leverages Template Injection in recent phishing campaigns

Type: Campaign | Issue Date : 15-05-2020 | TLP: Amber | Industry: All | Region: All | Serial: A-TR-EN-01-12947

MITRE ATT&CK®:Tactics & Software

Initial Access, Execution, Persistence, Defense Evasion, Discovery, Command and Control, Exfiltration.

Relevance

Industry: All.

Lazarus has historically targeted cross-industry organizations across different geographic regions, for both financial gain and espionage.

Summary

·        Between April and May 2020, Deloitte Internal Sources observed multiple phishing campaigns featuring Aviation, Defense & Space and US-South Korea relationship lures to drop a malicious DLL for further exploitation.

·        Deloitte CTI assesses these campaigns were initiated by Lazarus, a sophisticated threat actor group believed to be operating in the general interests of North Korea. This assessment is based on a significant tactics, techniques, and procedures (TTP) overlap with previous campaigns affiliated with Lazarus. Deloitte CTI further assesses Lazarus's primary motive in these campaigns was cyber espionage. We have high confidence in these assessments.

·        As previously noted by Deloitte CTI, weaponized documents continue to be a preferred method of secondary payload distribution in both financially-motivated as well as state sponsored campaigns. In this report, Deloitte CTI seeks to raise awareness of an effective defense evasion technique called Template Injection that Lazarus utilized to deliver and install malware.

 

Threat Analysis

Related actors: Lazarus

Infection Vector:Deloitte CTI cannot confirm the source of the examined documents but assesses with moderate confidence they were delivered via spearphishing email attachment (T1193).

Overview

Lazarus Threat Actor Group
Since mid-April 2019, Deloitte internal sources intercepted multiple weaponized documents used to deliver Lazarus-affiliated DLL files. These documents featured varying content used to appeal to different victims such as fake job openings at Boeing and BAE SYSTEMS, and a report about US-South Korean nuclear relationships. This report will dive into the technical details of these campaigns and detail how they were delivered and orchestrated.

Lazarus is a threat actor group that has been operating in the general interest of the North Korean government since at least 2009. The targets of Lazarus encompass a broad range of industries (public sector, finance, aerospace, software, entertainment) but demonstrate a persistent focus on diplomatic, military, and economic/trade-related organizations, which is typically indicative of cyber espionage. Deloitte CTI's investigation of phishing lures attributed to Lazarus from April and May 2020 indicates Lazarus sought to infect individuals that US-South Korean nuclear relationship pertains to them, as well as potential job candidates for aviation and defense companies.

Template Injection

Deloitte CTI's analysis indicated template injection (T1221) was used across all examined files to gain an initial foothold, which was leveraged to drop and install malicious DLL files discussed further. Template injection typically abuses Microsoft Office files of type DOCX, because they can fetch and subsequently load content hosted remotely, without prompting for user consent. Weaponized Microsoft DOCX files pose several unique challenges from a defensive standpoint, mainly due to the fact they are not malicious per-se. DOCX files do not support commonly-exploited Office features such as VBA macros, and hence are typically categorized as safe and are generally permitted to be attached to emails. For example, one of the Lazarus-linked weaponized DOCX analyzed below had a very low detection rate (1/71) when it first appeared on the multi engine antivirus scanner VirusTotal.

In a typical scenario, a threat actor will send a DOCX file via phishing, which upon execution fetches another Office document that supports VBA macros (i.e. DOTM) from a remote location. By doing so, the actor can deliver a macro-enabled document to victims, which would have been potently blocked by email security controls and organizational email policy if sent directly. It is important to note that this technique is primarily used to bypass security controls, and the victims will still have to enable the macros embedded in dropped DOTM files to get infected.

Template injection can also be utilized to steal NTLM credentials by triggering a force authentication to an attacker controller sever. To authenticate a client to a given server, Windows sends users' NTLM hash before receiving a requested resource. Threat actors can inject a server resource link to a DOCX file delivered via phishing, which points to an actor-controlled server. When that DOCX file gets loaded, the system will transfer the NTLM credentials via SMB or SMB's alternative Webdev to the actor's server.A prominent example of the use of this technique was brought into focus in late 2017, when the US-CERT reported it enabled credential theft in an unspecified advance persistent threat campaign targeting the energy and other critical infrastructure sectors.Deloitte CTI analysts have not found any evidence of credential theft via forced authentication in the campaigns examined in this report.

Campaign analysis

Although the phishing lures and their supporting infrastructure slightly differed between samples, the general execution scheme was similar and commenced as follows:

Figure 1: Execution flow scheme of April and May 2020 Lazarus-linked campaigns

 

 

On April 20, 2020, Deloitte CTI observed a document called "ROK Relations and Diplomatic Security 한미관계와 외교안보.docx" (MD5 - 4c239a926676087e31d82e79e838ced1), which had a very low detection rate on VirusTotal (1/71) when it first submitted for analysts (to date, the detection rate is 31/63). Once the user opens this DOCX file (T1204), the template injection technique is triggered and subsequently fetches a macro-enabled document of type DOCT/DOTM from od[.] lk/d/MzBfMjA1Njc0ODdf/pubmaterial.dotm, which redirects the user to web.opendrive[.] com (IP: 38[.]108.185.70). (figure 2)

Figure 2: Content retrieval from a URL shorting service Od[.]lk which redirects users to web.opendrive[.]com


In addition to the phishing lure presented in figure 3, the dropped file from web[.]opendrive[.]com (MD5- 2efbe6901fc3f479bc32aaf13ce8cf12) contains embedded macro code which relies on user execution to drop and load a malicious DLL. To note, this document also had a relatively low detection rate (14/63) when initially submitted for analysis on VirusTotal, which later increased to 37/61.

Figure 3: A US-South Korea relationship phishing lure that contains embedded macros.

Once macros are enabled (T1204), the document executes the embedded VBA code (T1064) that creates a DLL file (32 bit/64 bit version, based on the victim machine settings) in C:\Users\[USER]\AppData\Local\Microsoft\OneNote\onenote.db and then loads it using the "LoadLibraryA" (T1129) function. The content of the DLL file onenote.db (MD5: f4b55da7870e9ecd5f3f565f40490996) is double-base64 encoded and is located in an embedded VBA object called “UserForm1” (T1132).

Later, rundll32.exe(T1085) is invoked with the following parameters to execute onenote.db
C:\Windows\System32\rundll32.exe "C:\Users\[USER]\AppData\Local\Microsoft\OneNote\onenote.db",CMS_ContentInfo S-6-38-4412-76700627-315277-3247 0 0 18 1

Deloitte CTI identified multiple correlations between Lazarus previous operations and the discussed activities, which allowed us to attribute these campaigns to Lazarus. For example, the aforementioned unique identifier (S-6-38-4412-76700627-315277-3247) was observed in a Lazarus-linked November 2019 campaign [4]. In addition, both the macro code and the DLL file content share multiple similarities with former Lazarus-affiliated malware analyzed by security vendor Qianxin [5].

For persistence, the DLL code executes a function called “CoContentInfo” that creates a shortcut link file called onenote.lnk (T1023) in the startup folder (T1060): C:\users\[USER]\Appdata\Roaming\Microsoft\Windows\Start Menu\Programs\Startup\onenote.lnk (T1060) (MD5: d15399082ed8a6117993cb1893004249). After, it creates a registry key with a unique identifier “21401” which corresponds to the aforementioned shortcut file (figure 4 and 5).

Figure 4: Creation of onenote.lnk shortcut file

Figure 5: The unique identifier “21401”. Thisidentifier can be observed in the HKEY_CLASSES_ROOTCLSIDkey and corresponds to “Shortcut”.

The DLL file queriesfor the computer name, user name (T1082, T1087), drives, and process information (T1057) to collect information about the victim machine, user and running processes. This information is later encoded (T1022) and encrypted (T1132), before it is sent via HTTP POST (T1071) to a hard-coded command and control server www.elite4print [.] com (IP: 192[.]169.250.185) for further instructions.

Figure 6: API calls for collection user information and enumerating running processes

Deloitte CTI research indicated the dll file was configured to download and execute additional payloads (T1105), which Deloitte CTI assesses with moderate confidence were only delivered if the victim environment meets certain criteria aligned with campaign objectives. As of this writing, Deloitte CTI was unable to retrieve the subsequent executable file.

During our investigation, Deloitte CTI identified additional lures we associate with the same campaign which feature job openings at BAE systems and Boeing. The documents' weaponization technique and their DLL execution flow was largely similar, although they slightly differed in terms of defense evasion, execution parameters infrastructure and naming convention. For example, the Boeing lure retrieved a macro-enabled document from [https://www.sanlorenzoyacht[.]com/newsl/uploads/docs/43.dotm]https://www.sanlorenzoyacht[.]com/newsl/uploads/docs/43.dotm which later dropped the following dll file: C:\Users\[USER]\AppData\Local\Microsoft\Notice\wsuser.db. In addition, wsuser.db's content was packed with UPX to render the payload undetectable to security controls.The BAE system lure called [http://www[.]astedams.it/upload/frame/61.dotm]http://www[.]astedams.it/upload/frame/61.dotm and dropped the DLL file wsdts.db for the same purposes.

Figure 7: Additional Lazarus lures Deloitte CTI associates with the discussed campaign. The upper lure was called Senior_Design_Engineer.docx (MD5: 2449f61195e39f6264d4244dfa1d1613) and the lower Boeing_DSS_SE.docx (MD5: 9ea365c1714eb500e5f4a749a3ed0fe7)

Recommendations

Deloitte recommends the following:

·        Implementing and maintaining updated IDS/IPS to detect or block second stage payload retrieval communications from C2 infrastructure.

·        Educating users on current threats, the dangers of opening attachments or clicking links from untrusted sources, and the basic actions needed to prevent infection.

·        Using Group Policy Object (GPO) based corporate email controls to block users from enabling macros in Microsoft Office attachments typically used for malware downloaders/droppers - including both Word documents and Excel spreadsheets - originating from outside your network.

·        Monitoring for unauthorized changes to Registry with additional focus on the aforementioned locations.

·        Monitoring for anomalous parent-child process relationship.
